# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dnssec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] A **digital signature** is a mathematical scheme for verifying the authenticity of digital messages or documents.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] A valid digital signature on a message gives a recipient confidence that the message came from a sender known to the recipient.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Digital signatures are a type of public-key cryptography, and are commonly used for software distribution, financial transactions, contract management software, and in other cases where it is important to detect forgery or tampering.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Digital signatures are often used to implement electronic signatures, which include any electronic data that carries the intent of a signature, but not all electronic signatures use digital signatures.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] *Security* (existential unforgeability under chosen-message attack, or EUF-CMA): It should be computationally infeasible to generate a valid signature for a party without knowing that party's private key.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Here 1*n* refers to a unary number in the formalism of computational complexity theory.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] where *A**S*(*sk*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle, *S*(*sk*, · ), *Q* denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows the public key, *pk*, and the security parameter, *n*, and *x* ∉ *Q* denotes that the adversary may not directly query the string, *x*, on *S*.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman first described the notion of a digital signature scheme, although they only conjectured that such schemes existed based on functions that are trapdoor one-way permutations.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Soon afterwards, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman invented the RSA algorithm, which could be used to produce primitive digital signatures (although only as a proof-of-concept – "plain" RSA signatures are not secure).
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The first widely marketed software package to offer digital signature was Lotus Notes 1.0, released in 1989, which used the RSA algorithm.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Other digital signature schemes were soon developed after RSA, the earliest being Lamport signatures, Merkle signatures (also known as "Merkle trees" or simply "Hash trees"), and Rabin signatures.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In 1988, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Ronald Rivest became the first to rigorously define the security requirements of digital signature schemes.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] They described a hierarchy of attack models for signature schemes, and also presented the GMR signature scheme, the first that could be proved to prevent even an existential forgery against a chosen message attack, which is the currently accepted security definition for signature schemes.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The first such scheme which is not built on trapdoor functions but rather on a family of function with a much weaker required property of one-way permutation was presented by Moni Naor and Moti Yung.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] One digital signature scheme (of many) is based on RSA.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] To create signature keys, generate an RSA key pair containing a modulus, *N*, that is the product of two random secret distinct large primes, along with integers, *e* and *d*, such that *e* *d* ≡ 1 (mod *φ*(*N*)), where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The signer's public key consists of *N* and *e*, and the signer's secret key contains *d*.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Used directly, this type of signature scheme is vulnerable to key-only existential forgery attack.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] To create a forgery, the attacker picks a random signature σ and uses the verification procedure to determine the message, *m*, corresponding to that signature.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In practice, however, this type of signature is not used directly, but rather, the message to be signed is first hashed to produce a short digest, that is then padded to larger width comparable to *N*, then signed with the reverse trapdoor function.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] This forgery attack, then, only produces the padded hash function output that corresponds to σ, but not a message that leads to that value, which does not lead to an attack.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In the random oracle model, hash-then-sign (an idealized version of that practice where hash and padding combined have close to *N* possible outputs), this form of signature is existentially unforgeable, even against a chosen-plaintext attack.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] There are several reasons to sign such a hash (or message digest) instead of the whole document.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The signature will be much shorter and thus save time since hashing is generally much faster than signing in practice.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] A hash function can be used to convert an arbitrary input into the proper format.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Without the hash function, the text "to be signed" may have to be split (separated) in blocks small enough for the signature scheme to act on them directly.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] However, the receiver of the signed blocks is not able to recognize if all the blocks are present and in the appropriate order.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] As organizations move away from paper documents with ink signatures or authenticity stamps, digital signatures can provide added assurances of the evidence to provenance, identity, and status of an electronic document as well as acknowledging informed consent and approval by a signatory.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The United States Government Printing Office (GPO) publishes electronic versions of the budget, public and private laws, and congressional bills with digital signatures.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Universities including Penn State, University of Chicago, and Stanford are publishing electronic student transcripts with digital signatures.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] A message may have letterhead or a handwritten signature identifying its sender, but letterheads and handwritten signatures can be copied and pasted onto forged messages.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Even legitimate messages may be modified in transit.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] With a digital signature scheme, the central office can arrange beforehand to have a public key on file whose private key is known only to the branch office.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The branch office can later sign a message and the central office can use the public key to verify the signed message was not a forgery before acting on it.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] A forger who *doesn't* know the sender's private key can't sign a different message, or even change a single digit in an existing message without making the recipient's signature verification fail.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Non-repudiation, or more specifically non-repudiation of origin, is an important aspect of digital signatures.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] By this property, an entity that has signed some information cannot at a later time deny having signed it.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Similarly, access to the public key only does not enable a fraudulent party to fake a valid signature.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Note that these authentication, non-repudiation etc. properties rely on the secret key *not having been revoked* prior to its usage.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Public revocation of a key-pair is a required ability, else leaked secret keys would continue to implicate the claimed owner of the key-pair.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Checking revocation status requires an "online" check; e.g., checking a certificate revocation list or via the Online Certificate Status Protocol.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Very roughly this is analogous to a vendor who receives credit-cards first checking online with the credit-card issuer to find if a given card has been reported lost or stolen.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Of course, with stolen key pairs, the theft is often discovered only after the secret key's use, e.g., to sign a bogus certificate for espionage purpose.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In a *known message* attack, the attacker is given valid signatures for a variety of messages known by the attacker but not chosen by the attacker.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In an *adaptive chosen message* attack, the attacker first learns signatures on arbitrary messages of the attacker's choice.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] A universal forgery attack results in the ability to forge signatures for any message.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] A selective forgery attack results in a signature on a message of the adversary's choice.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] An existential forgery merely results in some valid message/signature pair not already known to the adversary.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The strongest notion of security, therefore, is security against existential forgery under an adaptive chosen message attack.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] All public key / private key cryptosystems depend entirely on keeping the private key secret.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] A more secure alternative is to store the private key on a smart card.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Many smart cards are designed to be tamper-resistant (although some designs have been broken, notably by Ross Anderson and his students).
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In a typical digital signature implementation, the hash calculated from the document is sent to the smart card, whose CPU signs the hash using the stored private key of the user, and then returns the signed hash.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Typically, a user must activate their smart card by entering a personal identification number or PIN code (thus providing two-factor authentication).
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] It can be arranged that the private key never leaves the smart card, although this is not always implemented.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] If the smart card is stolen, the thief will still need the PIN code to generate a digital signature.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] This reduces the security of the scheme to that of the PIN system, although it still requires an attacker to possess the card.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] A mitigating factor is that private keys, if generated and stored on smart cards, are usually regarded as difficult to copy, and are assumed to exist in exactly one copy.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Thus, the loss of the smart card may be detected by the owner and the corresponding certificate can be immediately revoked.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Private keys that are protected by software only may be easier to copy, and such compromises are far more difficult to detect.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Entering a PIN code to activate the smart card commonly requires a numeric keypad.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Some card readers have their own numeric keypad.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] This is safer than using a card reader integrated into a PC, and then entering the PIN using that computer's keyboard.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Readers with a numeric keypad are meant to circumvent the eavesdropping threat where the computer might be running a keystroke logger, potentially compromising the PIN code.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Specialized card readers are also less vulnerable to tampering with their software or hardware and are often EAL3 certified.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Smart card design is an active field, and there are smart card schemes which are intended to avoid these particular problems, despite having few security proofs so far.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a digital signature and a written signature is that the user does not "see" what they sign.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The user application presents a hash code to be signed by the digital signing algorithm using the private key.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] An attacker who gains control of the user's PC can possibly replace the user application with a foreign substitute, in effect replacing the user's own communications with those of the attacker.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] This could allow a malicious application to trick a user into signing any document by displaying the user's original on-screen, but presenting the attacker's own documents to the signing application.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] To protect against this scenario, an authentication system can be set up between the user's application (word processor, email client, etc.) and the signing application.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The general idea is to provide some means for both the user application and signing application to verify each other's integrity.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] For example, the signing application may require all requests to come from digitally signed binaries.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a cloud based digital signature service and a locally provided one is risk.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Many risk averse companies, including governments, financial and medical institutions, and payment processors require more secure standards, like FIPS 140-2 level 3 and FIPS 201 certification, to ensure the signature is validated and secure.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Technically speaking, a digital signature applies to a string of bits, whereas humans and applications "believe" that they sign the semantic interpretation of those bits.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In order to be semantically interpreted, the bit string must be transformed into a form that is meaningful for humans and applications, and this is done through a combination of hardware and software based processes on a computer system.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The problem is that the semantic interpretation of bits can change as a function of the processes used to transform the bits into semantic content.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] It is relatively easy to change the interpretation of a digital document by implementing changes on the computer system where the document is being processed.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] From a semantic perspective this creates uncertainty about what exactly has been signed.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] WYSIWYS (What You See Is What You Sign) means that the semantic interpretation of a signed message cannot be changed.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In particular this also means that a message cannot contain hidden information that the signer is unaware of, and that can be revealed after the signature has been applied.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] WYSIWYS is a requirement for the validity of digital signatures, but this requirement is difficult to guarantee because of the increasing complexity of modern computer systems.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The term WYSIWYS was coined by Peter Landrock and Torben Pedersen to describe some of the principles in delivering secure and legally binding digital signatures for Pan-European projects.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Digital signatures cryptographically bind an electronic identity to an electronic document and the digital signature cannot be copied to another document.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Paper contracts sometimes have the ink signature block on the last page, and the previous pages may be replaced after a signature is applied.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Digital signatures can be applied to an entire document, such that the digital signature on the last page will indicate tampering if any data on any of the pages have been altered, but this can also be achieved by signing with ink and numbering all pages of the contract.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Quality implementations: An implementation of a good algorithm (or protocol) with mistake(s) will not work.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Users (and their software) must carry out the signature protocol properly.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The private key must remain private: If the private key becomes known to any other party, that party can produce *perfect* digital signatures of anything.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The public key owner must be verifiable: A public key associated with Bob actually came from Bob.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] This is commonly done using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and the public key↔user association is attested by the operator of the PKI (called a certificate authority).
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] For 'open' PKIs in which anyone can request such an attestation (universally embodied in a cryptographically protected public key certificate), the possibility of mistaken attestation is non-trivial.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Commercial PKI operators have suffered several publicly known problems.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Such mistakes could lead to falsely signed, and thus wrongly attributed, documents.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] 'Closed' PKI systems are more expensive, but less easily subverted in this way.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Only if all of these conditions are met will a digital signature actually be any evidence of who sent the message, and therefore of their assent to its contents.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Legal enactment cannot change this reality of the existing engineering possibilities, though some such have not reflected this actuality.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] The first appears to have been in Utah in the United States, followed closely by the states Massachusetts and California.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Other countries have also passed statutes or issued regulations in this area as well and the UN has had an active model law project for some time.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Adoption of technical standards for digital signatures have lagged behind much of the legislation, delaying a more or less unified engineering position on interoperability, algorithm choice, key lengths, and so on what the engineering is attempting to provide.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Some industries have established common interoperability standards for the use of digital signatures between members of the industry and with regulators.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] These include the Automotive Network Exchange for the automobile industry and the SAFE-BioPharma Association for the healthcare industry.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] In several countries, a digital signature has a status somewhat like that of a traditional pen and paper signature, as in the 1999 EU digital signature directive and 2014 EU follow-on legislation.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Generally, these provisions mean that anything digitally signed legally binds the signer of the document to the terms therein.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] For that reason, it is often thought best to use separate key pairs for encrypting and signing.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Using the encryption key pair, a person can engage in an encrypted conversation (e.g., regarding a real estate transaction), but the encryption does not legally sign every message he or she sends.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Only when both parties come to an agreement do they sign a contract with their signing keys, and only then are they legally bound by the terms of a specific document.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] After signing, the document can be sent over the encrypted link.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] If a signing key is lost or compromised, it can be revoked to mitigate any future transactions.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] If an encryption key is lost, a backup or key escrow should be utilized to continue viewing encrypted content.
[src:dnssec/digital-signature] Signing keys should never be backed up or escrowed unless the backup destination is securely encrypted.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] A Domain Name System server translates a human-readable domain name (such as `example.com`) into a numerical IP address that is used to route communications between nodes.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] Normally if the server does not know a requested translation it will ask another server, and the process continues recursively.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] To increase performance, a server will typically remember (cache) these translations for a certain amount of time.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] This means if it receives another request for the same translation, it can reply without needing to ask any other servers, until that cache expires.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] When a DNS server has received a false translation and caches it for performance optimization, it is considered *poisoned*, and it supplies the false data to clients.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] If a DNS server is poisoned, it may return an incorrect IP address, diverting traffic to another computer (often an attacker's).
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] Normally, a networked computer uses a DNS server provided by an Internet service provider (ISP) or the computer user's organization.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] DNS servers are used in an organization's network to improve resolution response performance by caching previously obtained query results.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] Poisoning attacks on a single DNS server can affect the users serviced directly by the compromised server or those serviced indirectly by its downstream server(s) if applicable.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] To perform a cache poisoning attack, the attacker exploits flaws in the DNS software.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] A server should correctly validate DNS responses to ensure that they are from an authoritative source (for example by using DNSSEC); otherwise the server might end up caching the incorrect entries locally and serve them to other users that make the same request.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] This attack can be used to redirect users from a website to another site of the attacker's choosing.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] For example, an attacker spoofs the IP address DNS entries for a target website on a given DNS server and replaces them with the IP address of a server under their control.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] The attacker then creates files on the server under their control with names matching those on the target server.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] These files usually contain malicious content, such as computer worms or viruses.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] A user whose computer has referenced the poisoned DNS server gets tricked into accepting content coming from a non-authentic server and unknowingly downloads the malicious content.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] This technique can also be used for phishing attacks, where a fake version of a genuine website is created to gather personal details such as bank and credit/debit card details.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] The vulnerability of systems to DNS cache poisoning goes beyond its immediate effects as it can open users up to further risks such as phishing, malware injections, denial of service, and website hijacking due to system vulnerabilities.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] Various methods, ranging from the use of social engineering tactics to the exploitation of weaknesses present in the DNS server software, can lead to these attacks.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] In the following variants, the entries for the server ns.target.example would be poisoned and redirected to the attacker's name server at IP address *w.x.y.z*.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] These attacks assume that the name server for target.example is ns.target.example.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] To accomplish the attacks, the attacker must force the target DNS server to make a request for a domain controlled by one of the attacker's nameservers.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] The first variant of DNS cache poisoning involves redirecting the name server of the attacker's domain to the name server of the target domain, then assigning that name server an IP address specified by the attacker.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] DNS server's request: what are the address records for subdomain.attacker.example?
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] A vulnerable server would cache the additional A-record (IP address) for ns.target.example, allowing the attacker to resolve queries to the entire target.example domain.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] The second variant of DNS cache poisoning involves redirecting the nameserver of another domain unrelated to the original request to an IP address specified by the attacker.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] A vulnerable server would cache the unrelated authority information for target.example's NS-record (nameserver entry), allowing the attacker to resolve queries to the entire target.example domain.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] Many cache poisoning attacks against DNS servers can be prevented by being less trusting of the information passed to them by other DNS servers, and ignoring any DNS records passed back that are not directly relevant to the query.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] For example, versions of BIND 9.5.0-P1 and above perform these checks.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] Source port randomization for DNS requests, combined with the use of cryptographically secure random numbers for selecting both the source port and the 16-bit cryptographic nonce, can greatly reduce the probability of successful DNS race attacks.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] However, when routers, firewalls, proxies, and other gateway devices perform network address translation (NAT), or more specifically, port address translation (PAT), they may rewrite source ports in order to track connection state.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] When modifying source ports, PAT devices may remove source port randomness implemented by nameservers and stub resolvers.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] Secure DNS (DNSSEC) uses cryptographic digital signatures signed with a trusted public key certificate to determine the authenticity of data.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] DNSSEC can counter cache poisoning attacks.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] In 2010 DNSSEC was implemented in the Internet root zone servers, but needs to be deployed on all top level domain servers as well.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] The DNSSEC readiness of these is shown in the list of Internet top-level domains.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] As of 2020, all of the original TLDs support DNSSEC, as do country code TLDs of most large countries, but many country-code TLDs still do not.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] Many second-level domains also do not support DNSSEC.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] This kind of attack can be mitigated at the transport layer or application layer by performing end-to-end validation once a connection is established.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] A common example of this is the use of Transport Layer Security and digital signatures.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] For example, by using HTTPS (the secure version of HTTP), users may check whether the server's digital certificate is valid and belongs to a website's expected owner.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] Similarly, the secure shell remote login program checks digital certificates at endpoints (if known) before proceeding with the session.
[src:dnssec/dns-spoofing] For applications that download updates automatically, the application can embed a copy of the signing certificate locally and validate the signature stored in the software update against the embedded certificate.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The **Domain Name System Security Extensions** (**DNSSEC**) is a suite of extension specifications by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for securing data exchanged in the Domain Name System (DNS) in Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The protocol provides cryptographic authentication of data, authenticated denial of existence, and data integrity, but not availability or confidentiality.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of 2025, DNSSEC deployment is spotty.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The original design of the Domain Name System did not include any security features.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] It was conceived only as a scalable distributed system.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) attempt to add security, while maintaining backward compatibility.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] RFC 3833 of 2004 documents some of the known threats to the DNS, and their solutions in DNSSEC.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC was designed to protect applications using DNS from accepting forged or manipulated DNS data, such as that created by DNS cache poisoning.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] All answers from DNSSEC protected zones are digitally signed.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] By checking the digital signature, a DNS resolver is able to check if the information is identical (i.e. unmodified and complete) to the information published by the zone owner and served on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC *does not* provide confidentiality of data; in particular, all DNSSEC responses are authenticated but not encrypted.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC *does not* protect against DoS attacks directly, though it indirectly provides some benefit (because signature checking allows the use of potentially untrustworthy parties).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Other standards (not DNSSEC) are used to secure bulk data (such as a DNS zone transfer) sent between DNS servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As documented in RFC 4367, some users and developers make false assumptions about DNS names, such as assuming that a company's common name plus ".com" is always its domain name.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC cannot protect against false assumptions; it can only authenticate that the data is truly from or not available from the domain owner.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DNSSEC specifications (called *DNSSEC-bis*) describe the current DNSSEC protocol in great detail.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] With the publication of these new RFCs (March 2005), an earlier RFC, RFC 2535 has become obsolete.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The full set of RFCs that specify DNSSEC are collected in RFC 9364, which is also BCP 237.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of March 2026, DNSSEC is only operational in 83 (45%) of country code top-level domains.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] ICANN made DNSSEC mandatory for new generic top-level domains in 2014.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Verisign reported about 5% adoption in .net second-level domains and about 4% in .com.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Second-level domain adoption exceeds 50% in .nl (Netherlands), .cz (Czech Republic), .no (Norway), .se (Sweden), and .nu (Niue, but used to sound like "new").
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of 2023, major domains like google.com, amazon.com, and microsoft.com were unsigned.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC works by digitally signing records for DNS lookup using public-key cryptography.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The correct DNSKEY record is authenticated via a chain of trust, starting with a set of verified public keys for the DNS root zone which is the trusted third party.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Domain owners generate their own keys, and upload them using their DNS control panel at their domain-name registrar, which in turn pushes the keys via secDNS to the zone operator (e.g., Verisign for .com) who signs and publishes them in DNS.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS is implemented by the use of several resource records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains the DNSSEC signature for a record set.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS resolvers verify the signature with a public key, stored in a DNSKEY record.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains the public key that a DNS resolver uses to verify DNSSEC signatures in RRSIG records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] References a DNSKEY record in the sub-delegated zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DS record is placed in the parent zone along with the delegating NS records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains a link to the next record name in the zone and lists the record types that exist for the record's name.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS resolvers use NSEC records to verify the non-existence of a record name and type as part of DNSSEC validation.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains links to the next record name in the zone (in hashed name sorting order) and lists the record types that exist for the name covered by the hash value in the first label of the NSEC3 record's own name.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These records can be used by resolvers to verify the non-existence of a record name and type as part of DNSSEC validation.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NSEC3 records are similar to NSEC records, but NSEC3 uses cryptographically hashed record names to avoid the enumeration of the record names in a zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Authoritative DNS servers use this record to calculate and determine which NSEC3 records to include in responses to DNSSEC requests for non-existing names/types.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When DNSSEC is used, each answer to a DNS lookup contains an RRSIG DNS record, in addition to the record type that was requested.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The RRSIG record is a digital signature of the answer DNS resource record set.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The digital signature is verified by locating the correct public key found in a DNSKEY record.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The NSEC and NSEC3 records are used to provide cryptographic evidence of the non-existence of any Resource Record (RR).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DS record is used in the authentication of DNSKEYs in the lookup procedure using the chain of trust.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NSEC and NSEC3 records are used for robust resistance against spoofing.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC was designed to be extensible so that as attacks are discovered against existing algorithms, new ones can be introduced in a backward-compatible fashion as described in RFC 8624.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] From the results of a DNS lookup, a security-aware DNS resolver can determine whether the authoritative name server for the domain being queried supports DNSSEC, whether the answer it receives is secure, and whether there is some sort of error.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The lookup procedure is different for recursive name servers such as those of many ISPs, and for stub resolvers such as those included by default in mainstream operating systems.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Microsoft Windows uses a stub resolver, and Windows Server 2008 R2 and Windows 7 in particular use a non-validating but DNSSEC-aware stub resolver.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Using the chain of trust model, a Delegation Signer (DS) record in a parent domain (DNS zone) can be used to verify a DNSKEY record in a subdomain, which can then contain other DS records to verify further subdomains.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Say that a recursive resolver such as an ISP name server wants to get the IP addresses (A record and/or AAAA records) of the domain "www.example.com".
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When the resolver receives an answer via the normal DNS lookup process, it then checks to make sure that the answer is correct.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Ideally, the security-aware resolver would start with verifying the DS and DNSKEY records at the DNS root.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Then it would use the DS records for the "com" top-level domain found at the root to verify the DNSKEY records in the "com" zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] From there, it would see if there is a DS record for the "example.com" subdomain in the "com" zone, and if there were, it would then use the DS record to verify a DNSKEY record found in the "example.com" zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Finally, it would verify the RRSIG record found in the answer for the A records for "www.example.com".
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] There are several exceptions to the above example.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] First, if "example.com" does not support DNSSEC, there will be no RRSIG record in the answer and there will not be a DS record for "example.com" in the "com" zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] If there is a DS record for "example.com", but no RRSIG record in the reply, something is wrong and maybe a man in the middle attack is going on, stripping the DNSSEC information and modifying the A records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Or, it could be a broken security-oblivious name server along the way that stripped the DO flag bit from the query or the RRSIG record from the answer.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Next, it may be that there is not a domain name named "www.example.com", in which case instead of returning a RRSIG record in the answer, there will be either an NSEC record or an NSEC3 record.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These are "next secure" records that allow the resolver to prove that a domain name does not exist.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The NSEC/NSEC3 records have RRSIG records, which can be verified as above.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Finally, it may be that the "example.com" zone implements DNSSEC, but either the "com" zone or the root zone do not, creating an "island of security" which needs to be validated in some other way.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of 15 July 2010, deployment of DNSSEC to root is completed.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The .com domain was signed with valid security keys and the secure delegation was added to the root zone on 1 April 2011.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A *validating stub resolver* can also potentially perform its own signature validation by setting the Checking Disabled (CD) bit in its query messages.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A validating stub resolver uses the CD bit to perform its own recursive authentication.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Using such a validating stub resolver gives the client end-to-end DNS security for domains implementing DNSSEC, even if the Internet service provider or the connection to them is not trusted.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Non-validating stub resolvers must rely on external DNSSEC validation services, such as those controlled by the user's Internet service provider or a public recursive name server, and the communication channels between itself and those name servers, using methods such as DNS over TLS.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To be able to prove that a DNS answer is correct, one needs to know at least one key or DS record that is correct from sources other than the DNS.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These starting points are known as **trust anchors** and are typically obtained with the operating system or via some other trusted source.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When DNSSEC was originally designed, it was thought that the only trust anchor that would be needed was for the DNS root.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The root anchors were first published on 15 July 2010.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] An *authentication chain* is a series of linked DS and DNSKEY records, starting with a trust anchor to the authoritative name server for the domain in question.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Without a complete authentication chain, an answer to a DNS lookup cannot be securely authenticated.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To limit replay attacks, there are not only the normal DNS TTL values for caching purposes, but additional timestamps in RRSIG records to limit the validity of a signature.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Unlike TTL values which are relative to when the records were sent, the timestamps are absolute.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This means that all security-aware DNS resolvers must have clocks that are fairly closely in sync, say to within a few minutes.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These timestamps imply that a zone must regularly be re-signed and re-distributed to secondary servers, or the signatures will be rejected by validating resolvers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC involves many different keys, stored both in DNSKEY records, and from other sources to form trust anchors.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In order to allow for replacement keys, a **key rollover** scheme is required.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Typically, this involves first rolling out new keys in new DNSKEY records, in addition to the existing old keys.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Then, when it is safe to assume that the time to live values have caused the caching of old keys to have passed, these new keys can be used.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Finally, when it is safe to assume that the caching of records using the old keys have expired, the old DNSKEY records can be deleted.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This process is more complicated for things such as the keys to trust anchors, such as at the root, which may require an update of the operating system.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Keys in DNSKEY records can be used for two different things and typically different DNSKEY records are used for each.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] First, there are **key signing keys** (KSK) which are used to sign other DNSKEY records containing **zone signing keys** (ZSK), which are used to sign other records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Since the ZSKs are under complete control and use by one particular DNS zone, they can be switched more easily and more often.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As a result, ZSKs can be much shorter than KSKs and still offer the same level of protection while reducing the size of the RRSIG/DNSKEY records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When a new KSK is created, the DS record must be transferred to the parent zone and published there.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DS records use a message digest of the KSK instead of the complete key in order to keep the size of the records small.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is helpful for zones such as the .com domain, which are very large.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The procedure to update DS keys in the parent zone is also simpler than earlier DNSSEC versions that required DNSKEY records to be in the parent zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A closely related principle is that of **Algorithm rollover**, this involves migrating a zone from one signing Algorithm to another.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A good example of this would be migrating from Algorithm 8 (RSA/SHA-256) to Algorithm 13 (ECDSA/SHA-256).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Several ccTLD's have already migrated including .at, .br, .cz, .ch, .fr, .ie, .nl and .ph.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Verisign migrated .com, .net and .edu to Algorithm 13 in late 2023.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The migration of the root domain from Algorithm 8 to Algorithm 13 is currently in planning as of early 2024.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) is an IETF working group with the goal of developing protocols and techniques that allow Internet applications to establish cryptographically secured communications with TLS, DTLS, SMTP, and S/MIME based on DNSSEC.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The new protocols will enable additional assurances and constraints for the traditional model based on public key infrastructure.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] They will also enable domain holders to assert certificates for themselves, without reference to third-party certificate authorities.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Support for DNSSEC stapled certificates was enabled in Google Chrome 14, but was later removed.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] For Mozilla Firefox, support was provided by an add-on up to Firefox 56, while native support was proposed but ultimately rejected.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS is a critical and fundamental Internet service, yet in 1990 Steve Bellovin discovered serious security flaws in it.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Research into securing it began, and progressed dramatically when his paper was made public in 1995.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The initial RFC 2065 was published by the IETF in 1997, and initial attempts to implement that specification led to a revised (and believed fully workable) specification in 1999 as IETF RFC 2535.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Plans were made to deploy DNSSEC based on RFC 2535.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Unfortunately, the IETF RFC 2535 specification had very significant problems scaling up to the full Internet; by 2001 it became clear that this specification was unusable for large networks.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In normal operation DNS servers often get out of sync with their parents.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This isn't usually a problem, but when DNSSEC is enabled, this out-of-sync data could have the effect of a serious self-created denial of service.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Also, public key changes could have absurd effects; for example, if the ".com" zone changed its public key, it would have to send 22 million records (because it would need to update all of the signatures in all of its children).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus, DNSSEC as defined in RFC 2535 could not scale up to the Internet.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The IETF fundamentally modified DNSSEC, which is called *DNSSEC-bis* when necessary to distinguish it from the original DNSSEC approach of RFC 2535.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This new version uses "delegation signer (DS) resource records" to provide an additional level of indirection at delegation points between a parent and child zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In the new approach, when a child's master public key changes, instead of having six messages for every record in the child, there is one simple message: the child sends the new public key to its parent (signed, of course).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Parents simply store one master public key for each child; this is much more practical.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This means that a little data is pushed to the parent, instead of massive amounts of data being exchanged between the parent and children.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This does mean that clients have to do a little more work when verifying keys.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] More specifically, verifying a DNS zone's KEY RRset requires two signature verification operations instead of the one required by RFC 2535 (there is no impact on the number of signatures verified for other types of RRsets).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Most view this as a small price to pay, since it makes DNSSEC deployment more practical.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The new version is published in RFC4033-4035.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In January 2024, a "KeyTrap" denial-of-service attack was announced for all specification-respecting DNSSEC resolvers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DNSSEC specification (RFC4033-4035) specifies that a resolver, when receiving a signed packet from the upstream, should try *all* keys with the correct "tag" on *all* signatures until one of the combinations successfully verifies.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] By putting many keys with the same "tag" and many signatures corresponding to that "tag" in a packet, the researchers can slow down a resolver by a factor of 2 million.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In response, resolvers began to place limits on the amount of verification errors, key tag collisions, and hash calculations.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Cryptographically proving the absence of a domain requires signing the response to every query for a non-existent domain.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is not a problem for online signing servers, which keep their keys available online.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] However, DNSSEC was designed around using offline computers to sign records so that zone-signing-keys could be kept in cold storage.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This represents a problem when trying to authenticate responses to queries for non-existent domains since it is impossible to pre-generate a response to every possible hostname query.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The initial solution was to create NSEC records for every pair of domains in a zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus if a client queried for a record at the non-existent `k.example.com`, the server would respond with an NSEC record stating that nothing exists between `a.example.com` and `z.example.com`.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] However, this leaks more information about the zone than traditional unauthenticated NXDOMAIN errors because it exposes the existence of real domains.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The NSEC3 records (RFC 5155) were created as an alternative which hashes the name instead of listing them directly.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Over time, advancements in hashing using GPUs and dedicated hardware meant that NSEC3 responses could be cheaply brute forced using offline dictionary attacks.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NSEC5 has been proposed to allow authoritative servers to sign NSEC responses without having to keep a private key that can be used to modify the zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus stealing an NSEC5KEY would only result in the ability to more easily enumerate a zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Due to the messy evolution of the protocol and a desire to preserve backwards compatibility, online DNSSEC signing servers return a "white lie" instead of authenticating a denial of existence directly.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The technique outlined in RFC 4470 returns a NSEC record in which the pairs of domains lexically surround the requested domain.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] For example, request for `k.example.com` would thus result in an NSEC record proving that nothing exists between the (fictitious) domains `j.example.com` and `l.example.com`.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is also possible with NSEC3 records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Cloudflare pioneered a pair of alternative approaches, which manage to achieve the same result in one third of the response size.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The first is a variation on the "white lies" approach, called "black lies", which exploits common DNS client behavior to state the nonexistence more compactly.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The second approach instead chooses to prove that "the record exists but the requested record type does not", which they call "DNS shotgun".
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Internet is critical infrastructure, yet its operation depends on the fundamentally insecure DNS.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus, there is strong incentive to secure DNS, and deploying DNSSEC is generally considered to be a critical part of that effort.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] *National Strategy to Secure Cyberspace* specifically identified the need to secure DNS.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Wide-scale deployment of DNSSEC could resolve many other security problems as well, such as secure key distribution for e-mail addresses.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC deployment in large-scale networks is also challenging.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC can be deployed at any level of a DNS hierarchy, but it must be widely available in a zone before many others will want to adopt it.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS servers must be updated with software that supports DNSSEC, and DNSSEC data must be created and added to the DNS zone data.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A TCP/IP-using client must have their DNS resolver (client) updated before it can use DNSSEC's capabilities.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] What is more, any resolver must have, or have a way to acquire, at least one public key that it can trust before it can start using DNSSEC.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC implementation can add significant load to some DNS servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Common DNSSEC-signed responses are far larger than the default UDP size of 512 bytes.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In theory, this can be handled through multiple IP fragments, but many "middleboxes" in the field do not handle these correctly.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Yet many current TCP implementations store a great deal of data for each TCP connection; heavily loaded servers can run out of resources simply trying to respond to a larger number of (possibly bogus) DNSSEC requests.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Some protocol extensions, such as TCP Cookie Transactions, have been developed to reduce this loading.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To address these challenges, significant effort is ongoing to deploy DNSSEC, because the Internet is so vital to so many organizations.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] ARIN is also signing their reverse zones.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In February 2007, TDC became the first Swedish ISP to start offering this feature to its customers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] IANA publicly tested a sample signed root since June 2007.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] During this period prior to the production signing of the root, there were also several alternative trust anchors.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The IKS Jena introduced one on January 19, 2006, the Internet Systems Consortium introduced another on March 27 of the same year, while ICANN themselves announced a third on February 17, 2009.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On June 2, 2009, Afilias, the registry service provider for Public Interest Registry's .org zone signed the .org TLD.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Afilias and PIR also detailed on September 26, 2008, that the first phase, involving large registrars it has a strong working relationship with ("friends and family") would be the first to be able to sign their domains, beginning "early 2009".
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On June 23, 2010, 13 registrars were listed as offering DNSSEC records for .ORG domains.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] VeriSign ran a pilot project to allow .com and .net domains to register themselves for the purpose of NSEC3 experimentation.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This goal was achieved on-schedule and Verisign's DNSSEC VP, Matt Larson, won InfoWorld's Technology Leadership Award for 2011 for his role in advancing DNSSEC.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC was first deployed at the root level on July 15, 2010.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is expected to greatly simplify the deployment of DNSSEC resolvers, since the root trust anchor can be used to validate any DNSSEC zone that has a complete chain of trust from the root.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Since the chain of trust must be traced back to a trusted root without interruption in order to validate, trust anchors must still be configured for secure zones if any of the zones above them are not secure.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] For example, if the zone "signed.example.org" was secured but the "example.org" zone was not, then, even though the ".org" zone and the root are signed, a trust anchor has to be deployed in order to validate the zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In September 2008, ICANN and VeriSign each published implementation proposals and in October, the National Telecommunications and Information Administration (NTIA) asked the public for comments.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] It is unclear if the comments received affected the design of the final deployment plan.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On June 3, 2009, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) announced plans to sign the root by the end of 2009, in conjunction with ICANN, VeriSign and the NTIA.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On October 6, 2009, at the 59th RIPE Conference meeting, ICANN and VeriSign announced the planned deployment timeline for deploying DNSSEC within the root zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] At the meeting it was announced that it would be incrementally deployed to one root name server a month, starting on December 1, 2009, with the final root name server serving a DNSSEC signed zone on July 1, 2010, and the root zone will be signed with a RSA/SHA256 DNSKEY.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] During the incremental roll-out period the root zone will serve a *Deliberately Unvalidatable Root Zone* (DURZ) that uses dummy keys, with the final DNSKEY record not being distributed until July 1, 2010.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This means the keys that were used to sign the zone use are deliberately unverifiable; the reason for this deployment was to monitor changes in traffic patterns caused by the larger responses to queries requesting DNSSEC resource records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The .org top-level domain was signed with DNSSEC in June 2010, followed by .com, .net, and .edu later in 2010 and 2011.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Country code top-level domains were able to deposit keys starting in May 2010.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of November 2011 more than 25% of top-level domains are signed with DNSSEC.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On January 25, 2010, the L (ell) root server began serving a *Deliberately Unvalidatable Root Zone* (DURZ).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The zone uses signatures of a SHA-2 (SHA-256) hash created using the RSA algorithm, as defined in RFC 5702.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of May 2010, all thirteen root servers began serving the DURZ.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On July 15, 2010, the first root full production DNSSEC root zone was signed, with the SOA serial 2010071501.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Root trust anchors are available from IANA.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Underneath the root there is a large set of top-level domains that must be signed in order to achieve full DNSSEC deployment.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The List of Internet top-level domains provides details about which of the existing top-level domains have been signed and linked to the root.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In March 2006, the Internet Systems Consortium introduced the DNSSEC Lookaside Validation registry.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DLV was intended to make DNSSEC easier to deploy in the absence of a root trust anchor.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] At the time it was imagined that a validator might have to maintain large numbers of trust anchors corresponding to signed subtrees of the DNS.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The purpose of DLV was to allow validators to offload the effort of managing a trust anchor repository to a trusted third party.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DLV registry maintained a central list of trust anchors, instead of each validator repeating the work of maintaining its own list.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To use DLV, a validator that supports it was needed, such as BIND or Unbound, configured with a trust anchor for a DLV zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This zone contained DLV records; these had exactly the same format as DS records, but instead of referring to a delegated sub-zone, they referred to a zone elsewhere in the DNS tree.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When the validator could not find a chain of trust from the root to the RRset it is trying to check, it searched for a DLV record that could provide an alternative chain of trust.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Gaps in the chain of trust, such as unsigned top-level domains or registrars that did not support DNSSEC delegations, meant administrators of lower-level domains could use DLV to allow their DNS data to be validated by resolvers which had been configured to use DLV.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This may have hindered DNSSEC deployment by taking pressure off registrars and TLD registries to properly support DNSSEC.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DLV also added complexity by adding more actors and code paths for DNSSEC validation.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] ISC decommissioned its DLV registry in 2017.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DLV support was deprecated in BIND 9.12 and completely removed from BIND 9.16.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Unbound version 1.5.4 (July 2015) marked DLV as decommissioned in the example configuration and manual page.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Knot Resolver and PowerDNS Recursor never implemented DLV.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In March 2020, the IETF published RFC 8749, retiring DLV as a standard and moving RFC 4432 and RFC 5074 to "Historic" status.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Science and Technology Directorate of the U.S.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Department of Homeland Security (DHS) sponsors the "DNSSEC Deployment Initiative".
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] It was reported that on March 30, 2007, the U.S.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Department of Homeland Security proposed "to have the key to sign the DNS root zone solidly in the hands of the US government." However no U.S.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Government officials were present in the meeting room and the comment that sparked the article was made by another party.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DHS later commented on why they believe others jumped to the false conclusion that the U.S.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Government had made such a proposal: "The U.S.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Department of Homeland Security is funding the development of a technical plan for implementing DNSSec, and last October distributed an initial draft of it to a long list of international experts for comments.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The draft lays out a series of options for who could be the holder, or "operator," of the Root Zone Key, essentially boiling down to a governmental agency or a contractor.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) published NIST Special Publication 800-81 Secure Domain Name System (DNS) Deployment Guide on May 16, 2006, with guidance on how to deploy DNSSEC.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NIST intended to release new DNSSEC Federal Information Security Management Act (FISMA) requirements in NIST SP800-53-R1, referencing this deployment guide.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] U.S. agencies would then have had one year after final publication of NIST SP800-53-R1 to meet these new FISMA requirements.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] However, at the time NSEC3 had not been completed.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NIST had suggested using split domains, a technique that is known to be possible but is difficult to deploy correctly, and has the security weaknesses noted above.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On 22 August 2008, the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) released a memorandum requiring U.S.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Federal Agencies to deploy DNSSEC across .gov sites; the .gov root must be signed by January 2009, and all subdomains under .gov must be signed by December 2009.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] While the memo focuses on .gov sites, the U.S.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Defense Information Systems Agency says it intends to meet OMB DNSSEC requirements in the .mil (U.S. military) domain as well.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Several ISPs have started to deploy DNSSEC-validating DNS recursive resolvers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Comcast became the first major ISP to do so in the United States, announcing their intentions on October 18, 2010 and completing deployment on January 11, 2012.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] According to a study at APNIC, the proportion of clients who exclusively use DNS resolvers that perform DNSSEC validation rose to 8.3% in May 2013.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] About half of these clients were using Google's public DNS resolver.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In September 2015, Verisign announced their free public DNS resolver service, and although unmentioned in their press releases, it also performs DNSSEC validation.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] By the beginning of 2016, APNIC's monitoring showed the proportion of clients who exclusively use DNS resolvers that perform DNSSEC validation had increased to about 15%.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Google's public recursive DNS server enabled DNSSEC validation on May 6, 2013.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] BIND, the most popular DNS management software, enables DNSSEC support by default since version 9.5.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Quad9 public recursive DNS has performed DNSSEC validation on its main 9.9.9.9 address since it was established on May 11, 2016.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Quad9 also provides an alternate service which does not perform DNSSEC validation, principally for debugging.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In September 2023, Microsoft announced it would utilize DNSSEC (via DANE) to verify the authenticity of certificates during SMTP communications.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Geoff Huston has argued that DNSSEC deployment should be given up.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In 2016, email provider Fastmail published a blog post stating that the company does not plan on implementing DNSSEC, referencing the many DNSSEC-related outages that had occurred around the time.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] More positive reactions have been put forward by internet infrastructure corporation Cloudflare, which hired one of the founders of DNSSEC to help implement it at the company.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Domain registry Spaceship (a brand owned by Namecheap) enables DNSSEC automatically for supported domains it hosts the nameservers of.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In 2025, Dutch registry SIDN argued against the claim that DNSSEC is complex when compared to other internet protocols.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC deployment requires software on the server and client side.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The **Domain Name System** (**DNS**) is a hierarchical and distributed name service that provides a naming system for computers, services, and other resources on the Internet or other Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] It associates various information with *domain names* (identification strings) assigned to each of the associated entities.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Most prominently, it translates readily memorized domain names to the numerical IP addresses needed for locating and identifying computer services and devices with the underlying network protocols.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System has been an essential component of the functionality of the Internet since 1985.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System delegates the responsibility of assigning domain names and mapping those names to Internet resources by designating authoritative name servers for each domain.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Network administrators may delegate authority over subdomains of their allocated name space to other name servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This mechanism provides distributed and fault-tolerant service and was designed to avoid a single large central database.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In addition, the DNS specifies the technical functionality of the database service that is at its core.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] It defines the DNS protocol, a detailed specification of the data structures and data communication exchanges used in the DNS, as part of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces, the domain name hierarchy and the IP address spaces.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System maintains the domain name hierarchy and provides translation services between it and the address spaces.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Internet name servers and a communication protocol implement the Domain Name System.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records for a domain; a DNS name server responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The most common types of records stored in the DNS database are for start of authority (SOA), IP addresses (A and AAAA), SMTP mail exchangers (MX), name servers (NS), pointers for reverse DNS lookups (PTR), and domain name aliases (CNAME).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Although not intended to be a general-purpose database, DNS has been expanded over time to store records for other types of data for either automatic lookups, such as DNSSEC records, or for human queries such as *responsible person* (RP) records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] As a general-purpose database, the DNS has also been used in combating unsolicited email (spam) by storing blocklists.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The DNS database is conventionally stored in a structured text file, the zone file, but other database systems are common.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System originally used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as transport over IP.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Reliability, security, and privacy concerns spawned the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) as well as numerous other protocol developments.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] An often-used analogy to explain the DNS is that it serves as the phone book for the Internet by translating human-friendly computer hostnames into IP addresses.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The DNS can be quickly and transparently updated, allowing a service's location on the network to change without affecting the end users, who continue to use the same hostname.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Users take advantage of this when they use meaningful Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) and e-mail addresses without having to know how the computer actually locates the services.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] An important and ubiquitous function of the DNS is its central role in distributed Internet services such as cloud services and content delivery networks.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] When a user accesses a distributed Internet service using a URL, the domain name of the URL is translated to the IP address of a server that is proximal to the user.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The key functionality of the DNS exploited here is that different users can *simultaneously* receive different translations for the *same* domain name, a key point of divergence from a traditional phone-book view of the DNS.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This process of using the DNS to assign proximal servers to users is key to providing faster and more reliable responses on the Internet and is widely used by most major Internet services.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The DNS reflects the structure of administrative responsibility on the Internet.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Each subdomain is a zone of administrative autonomy delegated to a manager.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For zones operated by a registry, administrative information is often complemented by the registry's RDAP and WHOIS services.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] That data can be used to gain insight on, and track responsibility for, a given host on the Internet.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Using a simpler, more memorable name in place of a host's numerical address dates back to the ARPANET era.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) maintained a text file named HOSTS.TXT that mapped host names to the numerical addresses of computers on the ARPANET.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Elizabeth Feinler developed and maintained the first ARPANET directory.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Maintenance of numerical addresses, called the Assigned Numbers List, was handled by Jon Postel at the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute (ISI), whose team worked closely with SRI.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Computers, including their hostnames and addresses, were added to the primary file by contacting the SRI Network Information Center (NIC), directed by Feinler, via telephone during business hours.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Later, Feinler set up a WHOIS directory on a server in the NIC for retrieval of information about resources, contacts, and entities.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] She and her team developed the concept of domains.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Feinler suggested that domains should be based on the location of the physical address of the computer.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Computers at educational institutions would have the domain *edu*, for example.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] She and her team managed the Host Naming Registry from 1972 to 1989.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] By the early 1980s, maintaining a single, centralized host table had become slow and unwieldy and the emerging network required an automated naming system to address technical and personnel issues.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Postel directed the task of forging a compromise between five competing proposals of solutions to Paul Mockapetris.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Mockapetris instead created the Domain Name System in 1983 while at the University of Southern California.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Internet Engineering Task Force published the original specifications in RFC 882 and RFC 883 in November 1983.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] These were updated in RFC 973 in January 1986.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In 1984, four UC Berkeley students, Douglas Terry, Mark Painter, David Riggle, and Songnian Zhou, wrote the first Unix name server implementation for the Berkeley Internet Name Domain, commonly referred to as BIND.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In 1985, Kevin Dunlap of DEC substantially revised the DNS implementation.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Mike Karels, Phil Almquist, and Paul Vixie then took over BIND maintenance.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Internet Systems Consortium was founded in 1994 by Rick Adams, Paul Vixie, and Carl Malamud, expressly to provide a home for BIND development and maintenance.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] BIND versions from 4.9.3 onward were developed and maintained by ISC, with support provided by ISC's sponsors.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] As co-architects/programmers, Bob Halley and Paul Vixie released the first production-ready version of BIND version 8 in May 1997.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Since 2000, over 43 different core developers have worked on BIND.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In November 1987, RFC 1034 and RFC 1035 superseded the 1983 DNS specifications.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Several additional Request for Comments have proposed extensions to the core DNS protocols.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The domain name space consists of a tree data structure.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Each node or leaf in the tree has a *label* and zero or more *resource records* (RR), which hold information associated with the domain name.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The domain name itself consists of the label, concatenated with the name of its parent node on the right, separated by a dot.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The tree sub-divides into *zones* beginning at the root zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A DNS zone may consist of as many domains and subdomains as the zone manager chooses.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS can also be partitioned according to *class* where the separate classes can be thought of as an array of parallel namespace trees.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Administrative responsibility for any zone may be divided by creating additional zones.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Authority over the new zone is said to be *delegated* to a designated name server.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The parent zone ceases to be authoritative for the new zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The definitive descriptions of the rules for forming domain names appear in RFC 1035, RFC 1123, RFC 2181, and RFC 5892.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A domain name consists of one or more parts, technically called *labels*, that are conventionally concatenated, and delimited by dots, such as example.com.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The right-most label conveys the top-level domain; for example, the domain name www.example.com belongs to the top-level domain *com*.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The hierarchy of domains descends from right to left; each label to the left specifies a subdivision, or subdomain of the domain to the right.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For example, the label *example* specifies a subdomain of the *com* domain, and *www* is a subdomain of example.com.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This tree of subdivisions may have up to 127 levels.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A label may contain zero to 63 characters, because the length is only allowed to take 6 bits.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The null label of length zero is reserved for the root zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The full domain name may not exceed the length of 253 characters in its textual representation (or 254 with the trailing dot).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In the internal binary representation of the DNS this maximum length of 253 requires 255 octets of storage, as it also stores the length of the first of many labels and adds last null byte.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] 255 length is only achieved with at least 6 labels (counting the last null label).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Although no technical limitation exists to prevent domain name labels from using any character that is representable by an octet, hostnames use a preferred format and character set.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The characters allowed in labels are a subset of the ASCII character set, consisting of characters *a* through *z*, *A* through *Z*, digits *0* through *9*, and hyphen.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Domain names are interpreted in a case-independent manner.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Labels may not start or end with a hyphen.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] An additional rule requires that top-level domain names should not be all-numeric.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The limited set of ASCII characters permitted in the DNS prevented the representation of names and words of many languages in their native alphabets or scripts.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] To make this possible, ICANN approved the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system, by which user applications, such as web browsers, map Unicode strings into the valid DNS character set using Punycode.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In 2009, ICANN approved the installation of internationalized domain name country code top-level domains (*ccTLD*s).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In addition, many registries of the existing top-level domain names (*TLD*s) have adopted the IDNA system, guided by RFC 5890, RFC 5891, RFC 5892, RFC 5893.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System is maintained by a distributed database system, which uses the client–server model.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The nodes of this database are the name servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Each domain has at least one authoritative DNS server that publishes information about that domain and the name servers of any domains subordinate to it.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The top of the hierarchy is served by the root name servers, the servers to query when looking up (*resolving*) a TLD.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] An authoritative name server can either be a *primary* server or a *secondary* server.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Historically the terms *master/slave* and *primary/secondary* were sometimes used interchangeably but the current practice is to use the latter form.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A primary server is a server that stores the original copies of all zone records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A secondary server uses a special automatic updating mechanism in the DNS protocol in communication with its primary to maintain an identical copy of the primary records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Every DNS zone must be assigned a set of authoritative name servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This set of servers is stored in the parent domain zone with name server (NS) records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] An authoritative server indicates its status of supplying definitive answers, deemed *authoritative*, by setting a protocol flag, called the "*Authoritative Answer*" (*AA*) bit in its responses.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] When a name server is designated as the authoritative server for a domain name for which it does not have authoritative data, it presents a type of error called a "lame delegation" or "lame response".
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Domain name resolvers determine the domain name servers responsible for the domain name in question by a sequence of queries starting with the right-most (top-level) domain label.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For proper operation of its domain name resolver, a network host is configured with an initial cache (*hints*) of the known addresses of the root name servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The hints are updated periodically by an administrator by retrieving a dataset from a reliable source.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Assuming the resolver has no cached records to accelerate the process, the resolution process starts with a query to one of the root servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In typical operation, the root servers do not answer directly, but respond with a referral to more authoritative servers, e.g., a query for "www.wikipedia.org" is referred to the *org* servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The resolver now queries the servers referred to, and iteratively repeats this process until it receives an authoritative answer.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The diagram illustrates this process for the host that is named by the fully qualified domain name "www.wikipedia.org".
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This mechanism would place a large traffic burden on the root servers, if every resolution on the Internet required starting at the root.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In practice caching is used in DNS servers to off-load the root servers, and as a result, root name servers actually are involved in only a relatively small fraction of all requests.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In theory, authoritative name servers are sufficient for the operation of the Internet.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] However, with only authoritative name servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system would have to implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Typically, such caching DNS servers also implement the recursive algorithm necessary to resolve a given name starting with the DNS root through to the authoritative name servers of the queried domain.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] With this function implemented in the name server, user applications gain efficiency in design and operation.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The combination of DNS caching and recursive functions in a name server is not mandatory; the functions can be implemented independently in servers for special purposes.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Internet service providers (ISP) typically provide recursive and caching name servers for their customers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In addition, many home networking routers implement DNS caches and recursion to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The client side of the DNS is called a DNS resolver.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A resolver is responsible for initiating and sequencing the queries that ultimately lead to a full resolution (translation) of the resource sought, e.g., translation of a domain name into an IP address.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers are classified by a variety of query methods, such as *recursive*, *non-recursive*, and *iterative*.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A resolution process may use a combination of these methods.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In a *non-recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a DNS server that provides a record either for which the server is authoritative, or it provides a partial result without querying other servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In case of a caching DNS resolver, the non-recursive query of its local DNS cache delivers a result and reduces the load on upstream DNS servers by caching DNS resource records for a period of time after an initial response from upstream DNS servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In a *recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a single DNS server, which may in turn query other DNS servers on behalf of the requester.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For example, a simple stub resolver running on a home router typically makes a recursive query to the DNS server run by the user's ISP.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A recursive query is one for which the DNS server answers the query completely by querying other name servers as needed.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In typical operation, a client issues a recursive query to a caching recursive DNS server, which subsequently issues non-recursive queries to determine the answer and send a single answer back to the client.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The resolver, or another DNS server acting recursively on behalf of the resolver, negotiates use of recursive service using bits in the query headers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS servers are not required to support recursive queries.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The *iterative query* procedure is a process in which a DNS resolver queries a chain of one or more DNS servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Each server refers the client to the next server in the chain, until the current server can fully resolve the request.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For example, a possible resolution of www.example.com would query a global root server, then a "com" server, and finally an "example.com" server.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Name servers in delegations are identified by name, rather than by IP address.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This means that a resolving name server must issue another DNS request to discover the IP address of the server to which it has been referred.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] If the name given in the delegation is a subdomain of the domain for which the delegation is being provided, there is a circular dependency.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In this case, the name server providing the delegation must also provide one or more IP addresses for the authoritative name server mentioned in the delegation.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The delegating name server provides this glue in the form of records in the *additional section* of the DNS response, and provides the delegation in the *authority section* of the response.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A glue record is a combination of the name server and IP address.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For example, if the authoritative name server for example.org is ns1.example.org, a computer trying to resolve www.example.org first resolves ns1.example.org.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] As ns1 is contained in example.org, this requires resolving example.org first, which presents a circular dependency.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] To break the dependency, the name server for the top level domain org includes glue along with the delegation for example.org.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The glue records are address records that provide IP addresses for ns1.example.org.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The resolver uses one or more of these IP addresses to query one of the domain's authoritative servers, which allows it to complete the DNS query.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A common approach to reduce the query load on DNS servers is to cache the results of name resolution locally or on intermediary resolver hosts.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Each DNS query result comes with a time to live (TTL), which indicates how long the information remains valid before it needs to be discarded or refreshed.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This TTL is determined by the administrator of the authoritative DNS server and can range from a few seconds to several days or even weeks.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] As a result of this distributed caching architecture, changes to DNS records do not propagate throughout the network immediately, but require all caches to expire and to be refreshed after the TTL.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] RFC 1912 conveys basic rules for determining appropriate TTL values.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Some resolvers may override TTL values, as the protocol supports caching for up to sixty-eight years or no caching at all.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Negative caching, i.e. the caching of the fact of non-existence of a record, is determined by name servers authoritative for a zone which must include the Start of Authority (SOA) record when reporting no data of the requested type exists.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The value of the *minimum* field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself is used to establish the TTL for the negative answer.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A reverse DNS lookup is a query of the DNS for domain names when the IP address is known.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Multiple domain names may be associated with an IP address.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The DNS stores IP addresses in the form of domain names as specially formatted names in pointer (PTR) records within the infrastructure top-level domain arpa.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For IPv6, the reverse lookup domain is ip6.arpa.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The IP address is represented as a name in reverse-ordered octet representation for IPv4, and reverse-ordered nibble representation for IPv6.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] When performing a reverse lookup, the DNS client converts the address into these formats before querying the name for a PTR record following the delegation chain as for any DNS query.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For example, assuming the IPv4 address 208.80.152.2 is assigned to Wikimedia, it is represented as a DNS name in reverse order: 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] When the DNS resolver gets a pointer (PTR) request, it begins by querying the root servers, which point to the servers of American Registry for Internet Numbers (ARIN) for the 208.in-addr.arpa zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] ARIN's servers delegate 152.80.208.in-addr.arpa to Wikimedia to which the resolver sends another query for 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa, which results in an authoritative response.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Users generally do not communicate directly with a DNS resolver.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Instead DNS resolution takes place transparently in applications such as web browsers, e-mail clients, and other Internet applications.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] When an application makes a request that requires a domain name lookup, such programs send a resolution request to the DNS resolver in the local operating system, which in turn handles the communications required.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The DNS resolver will almost invariably have a cache (see above) containing recent lookups.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] If the cache can provide the answer to the request, the resolver will return the value in the cache to the program that made the request.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] If the cache does not contain the answer, the resolver will send the request to one or more designated DNS servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In any event, the name server thus queried will follow the process outlined above, until it either successfully finds a result or does not.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] It then returns its results to the DNS resolver; assuming it has found a result, the resolver duly caches that result for future use, and hands the result back to the software which initiated the request.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Some large ISPs have configured their DNS servers to violate rules, such as by disobeying TTLs, or by indicating that a domain name does not exist just because one of its name servers does not respond.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Some applications such as web browsers maintain an internal DNS cache to avoid repeated lookups via the network.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This practice can add extra difficulty when debugging DNS issues as it obscures the history of such data.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] These caches typically use very short caching times on the order of one minute.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer represents a notable exception: versions up to IE 3.x cache DNS records for 24 hours by default.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer 4.x and later versions (up to IE 8) decrease the default timeout value to half an hour, which may be changed by modifying the default configuration.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] When Google Chrome detects issues with the DNS server it displays a specific error message.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System includes several other functions and features.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Hostnames and IP addresses are not required to match in a one-to-one relationship.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Multiple hostnames may correspond to a single IP address, which is useful in virtual hosting, in which many web sites are served from a single host.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Alternatively, a single hostname may resolve to many IP addresses to facilitate fault tolerance and load distribution to multiple server instances across an enterprise or the global Internet.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS serves other purposes in addition to translating names to IP addresses.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For instance, mail transfer agents use DNS to find the best mail server to deliver e-mail: An MX record provides a mapping between a domain and a mail exchanger; this can provide an additional layer of fault tolerance and load distribution.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The DNS is used for efficient storage and distribution of IP addresses of block-listed email hosts.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A common method is to place the IP address of the subject host into the sub-domain of a higher level domain name, and to resolve that name to a record that indicates a positive or a negative indication.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] E-mail servers can query blocklist.example to find out if a specific host connecting to them is in the block list.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Many such block lists, either subscription-based or free of cost, are available for use by email administrators and anti-spam software.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] To provide resilience in the event of computer or network failure, multiple DNS servers are usually provided for coverage of each domain.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] At the top level of global DNS, thirteen groups of root name servers exist, with additional "copies" of them distributed worldwide via anycast addressing.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS (DDNS) updates a DNS server with a client IP address on-the-fly, for example, when moving between ISPs or mobile hot spots, or when the IP address changes administratively.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The DNS protocol uses two types of DNS messages, queries and responses; both have the same format.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Each message consists of a header and four sections: question, answer, authority, and an additional space.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A header field (*flags*) controls the content of these four sections.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The header section consists of the following fields: *Identification*, *Flags*, *Number of questions*, *Number of answers*, *Number of authority resource records* (RRs), and *Number of additional RRs*.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Each field is 16 bits long, and appears in the order given.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The identification field is used to match responses with queries.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] After the flags word, the header ends with four 16-bit integers which contain the number of records in each of the sections that follow, in the same order.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Indicates if the message is a query (0) or a reply (1).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The type can be QUERY (standard query, 0), IQUERY (inverse query, 1), or STATUS (server status request, 2).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Authoritative Answer, in a response, indicates if the DNS server is authoritative for the queried hostname.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] TrunCation, indicates that this message was truncated due to excessive length.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Recursion Desired, indicates if the client means a recursive query.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Recursion Available, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server supports recursion.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Authentic Data, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server verified the data.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Checking Disabled, in a query, indicates that non-verified data is acceptable in a response.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Response code, can be NOERROR (0), FORMERR (1, Format error), SERVFAIL (2), NXDOMAIN (3, Nonexistent domain), etc.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The question section has a simpler format than the resource record format used in the other sections.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The domain name is broken into discrete labels which are concatenated; each label is prefixed by the length of that label.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System specifies a database of information elements for network resources.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The types of information elements are categorized and organized with a list of DNS record types, the resource records (RRs).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Each record has a type (name and number), an expiration time (time to live), a class, and type-specific data.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Resource records of the same type are described as a *resource record set* (RRset), having no special ordering.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers return the entire set upon query, but servers may implement round-robin ordering to achieve load balancing.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In contrast, the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) work on the complete set of resource record in canonical order.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The *CLASS* of a record is set to IN (for *Internet*) for common DNS records involving Internet hostnames, servers, or IP addresses.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In addition, the classes Chaos (CH) and Hesiod (HS) exist.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Each class is an independent name space with potentially different delegations of DNS zones.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In addition to resource records defined in a zone file, the domain name system also defines several request types that are used only in communication with other DNS nodes (*on the wire*), such as when performing zone transfers (AXFR/IXFR) or for EDNS (OPT).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The domain name system supports wildcard DNS records which specify names that start with the *asterisk label*, `*`, e.g., `*.example`.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS records belonging to wildcard domain names specify rules for generating resource records within a single DNS zone by substituting whole labels with matching components of the query name, including any specified descendants.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For example, in the following configuration, the DNS zone *x.example* specifies that all subdomains, including subdomains of subdomains, of *x.example* use the mail exchanger (MX) *a.x.example*.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The AAAA record for *a.x.example* is needed to specify the mail exchanger IP address.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] As this has the result of excluding this domain name and its subdomains from the wildcard matches, an additional MX record for the subdomain *a.x.example*, as well as a wildcarded MX record for all of its subdomains, must also be defined in the DNS zone.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The role of wildcard records was refined in RFC 4592, because the original definition in RFC 1034 was incomplete and resulted in misinterpretations by implementers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The original DNS protocol had limited provisions for extension with new features.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In 1999, Paul Vixie published in RFC 2671 (superseded by RFC 6891) an extension mechanism, called Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS) that introduced optional protocol elements without increasing overhead when not in use.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This was accomplished through the OPT pseudo-resource record that only exists in wire transmissions of the protocol, but not in any zone files.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Initial extensions were also suggested (EDNS0), such as increasing the DNS message size in UDP datagrams.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS updates use the UPDATE DNS opcode to add or remove resource records dynamically from a zone database maintained on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This facility is useful to register network clients into the DNS when they boot or become otherwise available on the network.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] As a booting client may be assigned a different IP address each time from a DHCP server, it is not possible to provide static DNS assignments for such clients.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] From the time of its origin in 1983 the DNS has used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for transport over IP.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Its limitations have motivated numerous protocol developments for reliability, security, privacy, and other criteria, in the following decades.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] UDP reserves port number 53 for servers listening to queries.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Such a query consists of a clear-text request sent in a single UDP packet from the client, responded to with a clear-text reply sent in a single UDP packet from the server.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] When the length of the answer exceeds 512 bytes and both client and server support Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS), larger UDP packets may be used.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Use of DNS over UDP is limited by, among other things, its lack of transport-layer encryption, authentication, reliable delivery, and message length.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In 1989, RFC 1123 specified optional Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transport for DNS queries, replies and, particularly, zone transfers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Via fragmentation of long replies, TCP allows longer responses, reliable delivery, and re-use of long-lived connections between clients and servers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For larger responses, the server refers the client to TCP transport.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS over TLS emerged as an IETF standard for encrypted DNS in 2016, utilizing Transport Layer Security (TLS) to protect the entire connection, rather than just the DNS payload.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] RFC 7858 specifies that opportunistic encryption and authenticated encryption may be supported, but did not make either server or client authentication mandatory.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS over HTTPS was developed as a competing standard for DNS query transport in 2018, tunneling DNS query data over HTTPS, which transports HTTP over TLS.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DoH was promoted as a more web-friendly alternative to DNS since, like DNSCrypt, it uses TCP port 443, and thus looks similar to web traffic, though they are easily differentiable in practice without proper padding.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] RFC 9250, published in 2022 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over QUIC.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] It has "privacy properties similar to DNS over TLS (DoT) [...], and latency characteristics similar to classic DNS over UDP".
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This method is not the same as DNS over HTTP/3.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] RFC 9953, published in 2026 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over CoAP.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The "application use case of DoC is inspired by DNS over HTTPS (DoH) (RFC 8484).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] However, DoC aims for deployment in the constrained Internet of Things (IoT), which usually conflicts with the requirements introduced by HTTPS." DoC outperforms other DNS resolution mechanisms in constrained scenarios.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Oblivious DNS (ODNS) was invented and implemented by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] ODoH combines ingress/egress separation (invented in ODNS) with DoH's HTTPS tunneling and TLS transport-layer encryption in a single protocol.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS may be run over virtual private networks (VPNs) and tunneling protocols.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The privacy gains of Oblivious DNS can be garnered through the use of the preexisting Tor network of ingress and egress nodes, paired with the transport-layer encryption provided by TLS.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt uses either TCP port 443, the same port as HTTPS encrypted web traffic, or UDP port 443.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This introduced not only privacy regarding the content of the query, but also a significant measure of firewall-traversal capability.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Privacy of user/query pairs is created, since the ingress node does not know the content of the query, while the egress node does not know the identity of the client.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt was first implemented in production by OpenDNS in December 2011.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] There are several free and open source software implementations that additionally integrate ODoH.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] It is available for a variety of operating systems, including Unix, Apple iOS, Linux, Android, and Windows.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Originally, security concerns were not major design considerations for DNS software or any software for deployment on the early Internet, as the network was not open for participation by the general public.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] However, the expansion of the Internet into the commercial sector in the 1990s changed the requirements for security measures to protect data integrity and user authentication.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Several vulnerability issues were discovered and exploited by malicious users.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] One such issue is DNS cache poisoning, in which data is distributed to caching resolvers under the pretense of being an authoritative origin server, thereby polluting the data store with potentially false information and long expiration times (time-to-live).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Subsequently, legitimate application requests may be redirected to network hosts operated with malicious intent.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS responses traditionally do not have a cryptographic signature, leading to many attack possibilities; the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) modify DNS to add support for cryptographically signed responses.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNSCurve has been proposed as an alternative to DNSSEC.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Other extensions, such as TSIG, add support for cryptographic authentication between trusted peers and are commonly used to authorize zone transfer or dynamic update operations.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Techniques such as forward-confirmed reverse DNS can also be used to help validate DNS results.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNS can also "leak" from otherwise secure or private connections, if attention is not paid to their configuration, and at times DNS has been used to bypass firewalls by malicious persons, and exfiltrate data, since it is often seen as innocuous.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Some domain names may be used to achieve spoofing effects.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For example, paypal.com and paypa1.com are different names, yet users may be unable to distinguish them in a graphical user interface depending on the user's chosen typeface.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In many fonts the letter *l* and the numeral *1* look very similar or even identical.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This problem, known as the IDN homograph attack, is acute in systems that support internationalized domain names, as many character codes in ISO 10646 may appear identical on typical computer screens.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This vulnerability is occasionally exploited in phishing.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger is a type of cyber attack technique that uses the DNS to communicate and control malware remotely without relying on conventional protocols that might raise red flags.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The DNSMessenger attack is covert because DNS is primarily used for domain name resolution and is often not closely monitored by network security tools, making it an effective channel for attackers to exploit.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This technique involves the use of DNS TXT records to send commands to infected systems.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Once malware has been surreptitiously installed on a victim's machine, it reaches out to a controlled domain to retrieve commands encoded in DNS text records.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This form of malware communication is stealthy, as DNS requests are usually allowed through firewalls, and because DNS traffic is often seen as benign, these communications can bypass many network security defenses.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger attacks can enable a wide array of malicious activities, from data exfiltration to the delivery of additional payloads, all while remaining under the radar of traditional network security measures.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Understanding and defending against such methods are crucial for maintaining robust cybersecurity.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Originally designed as a public, hierarchical, distributed and heavily cached database, the DNS protocol has no confidentiality controls.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] User queries and nameserver responses are sent unencrypted, enabling network packet sniffing, DNS hijacking, DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] This deficiency is commonly used by cybercriminals and network operators for marketing purposes, user authentication on captive portals and censorship.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] User privacy is further exposed by proposals for increasing the level of client IP information in DNS queries (RFC 7871) for the benefit of content delivery networks.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Solutions preventing DNS inspection by the local network operator have been criticized for thwarting corporate network security policies and Internet censorship.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Public DNS servers are also criticized for contributing to the centralization of the Internet by placing control over DNS resolution in the hands of the few large companies which can afford to run public resolvers.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The right to use a domain name is delegated by domain name registrars which are accredited by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) or other organizations such as OpenNIC, that are charged with overseeing the name and number systems of the Internet.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In addition to ICANN, each top-level domain (TLD) is maintained and serviced technically by an administrative organization, operating a registry.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A *registry* is responsible for operating the database of names within its authoritative zone, although the term is most often used for TLDs.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] A *registrant* is a person or organization who asked for domain registration.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The registry receives registration information from each domain name *registrar*, which is authorized (accredited) to assign names in the corresponding zone and publishes the information using the WHOIS protocol.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] As of 2015, usage of RDAP is being considered.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] ICANN publishes the complete list of TLDs, TLD registries, and domain name registrars.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Registrant information associated with domain names is maintained in an online database accessible with the WHOIS service.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For most of the more than 290 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs), the domain registries maintain the WHOIS (Registrant, name servers, expiration dates, etc.) information.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For instance, DENIC, Germany NIC, holds the DE domain data.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] From about 2001, most generic top-level domain (gTLD) registries have adopted this so-called *thick* registry approach, i.e. keeping the WHOIS data in central registries instead of registrar databases.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] For top-level domains on COM and NET, a *thin* registry model is used.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The domain registry (GoDaddy, BigRock and PDR, VeriSign, etc.) holds basic WHOIS data (i.e., registrar and name servers, etc.).
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] On the other hand, organizations, i.e., registrants using ORG, are on the Public Interest Registry exclusively.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] Some domain name registries, often called *network information centers* (NIC), also function as registrars to end-users, in addition to providing access to the WHOIS datasets.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The top-level domain registries, such as for the domains COM, NET, and ORG use a registry-registrar model consisting of many domain name registrars.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] In this method of management, the registry only manages the domain name database and the relationship with the registrars.
[src:dnssec/domain-name-system] The *registrants* (users of a domain name) are customers of the registrar, in some cases through additional subcontracting of resellers.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] A **root name server** is a name server for the root zone of the Domain Name System (DNS) of the Internet.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] It directly answers requests for records in the root zone and answers other requests by returning a list of the authoritative name servers for the appropriate top-level domain (TLD).
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The root name servers are a critical part of the Internet infrastructure because they are the first step in resolving human-readable host names into IP addresses that are used in communication between Internet hosts.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] A combination of limits in the DNS and certain protocols, namely the practical size of unfragmented User Datagram Protocol (UDP) packets, resulted in a decision to limit the number of root servers to thirteen server addresses.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] However, enabled by the use of anycast addressing, the actual number of root server instances—1954—is much larger, as of December 5, 2025.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The DNS is a hierarchical naming system for computers, services, or any resource participating in the Internet.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The top of that hierarchy is the root domain.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The root domain does not have a formal name and its label in the DNS hierarchy is an empty string.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] All fully qualified domain names (FQDNs) on the Internet can be regarded as ending with this empty string for the root domain, and therefore ending in a full stop character (the label delimiter), e.g., "www.example.com.".
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] This is generally implied rather than explicit, as modern DNS software does not actually require that the terminating dot be included when attempting to translate a domain name to an IP address.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The root domain contains all top-level domains of the Internet.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] As of July 2015, it contained 1058 TLDs, including 730 generic top-level domains (gTLDs) and 301 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs).
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] In addition, the root domain is used for technical name spaces in the management of Internet addressing and other resources, as well as for testing internationalized domain names.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] When a computer on the Internet needs to resolve a domain name, it uses DNS resolver software to perform the lookup.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] A resolver breaks the name up into its labels from right to left.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The first component (TLD) is queried using a root server to obtain the responsible authoritative server.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Queries for each label return more specific name servers until a name server returns the answer of the original query.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] In practice, most of this information does not change very often over a period of hours, and therefore it is cached by intermediate name servers or by a name cache built into the user's application.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] DNS lookups to the root name servers may therefore be relatively infrequent.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] A survey in 2003 reported that only 2% of all queries to the root servers were legitimate.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Incorrect or non-existent caching was responsible for 75% of the queries, 12.5% were for unknown TLDs, and 7% were for lookups using IP addresses as if they were domain names.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Some misconfigured desktop computers even tried to update the root server records for the TLDs.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] A similar list of observed problems and recommended fixes has been published in RFC 4697.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Resolvers use a small 3 KB *root.hints* file published by Internic to bootstrap this initial list of root server addresses; in other words, root.hints is necessary in order to break the circular dependency of needing to know the addresses of a root name server to lookup the same address.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] There are 13 logical root name servers specified, with logical names in the form *letter*.root-servers.net, where *letter* ranges from a to m.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The choice of 13 name servers was made because of limitations in the original DNS specification, which specifies a maximum packet size of 512 bytes when using the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Technically however, fourteen name servers fit into an IPv4 packet.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The addition of IPv6 addresses for the root name servers requires more than 512 bytes, which is facilitated by the EDNS0 extension to the DNS standard.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Although 13 root name servers are specified, this does not mean that there are only 13 physical servers; each operator uses redundant computer equipment so that it can continue providing reliable service even if server hardware or software fails.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Additionally, all operate in multiple geographical locations using a routing technique called anycast addressing, providing increased performance and even more fault tolerance.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] An informational homepage exists for every logical server (except G-Root) under the Root Server Technical Operations Association domain with web address in the form http://*letter*.root-servers.org/, where *letter* ranges from a to m.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Ten servers were originally in the United States; all are now operated using anycast addressing.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Three servers were originally located in Stockholm, Sweden (I-Root), Amsterdam, Netherlands (K-Root), and Tokyo, Japan (M-Root) respectively.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Older servers had their own name before the policy of using similar names was established.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Since the implementation of anycast addressing, most of the physical root servers are now outside the United States, allowing for high performance worldwide.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] A local instance is only visible to nearby networks, for example, particular exchange points.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] There are also several alternative namespace systems with an alternative DNS root using their own set of root name servers that exist in parallel to the mainstream name servers.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The first, AlterNIC, generated a substantial amount of press.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The function of a root name server may also be implemented locally, or on a provider network.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Such servers are synchronized with the official root zone file as published by ICANN, and do not constitute an alternate root.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] As the root name servers are an important part of the Internet, they have come under attack several times, although none of the attacks have ever been serious enough to severely affect the performance of the Internet.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The DNS Root Server System Advisory Committee is an ICANN committee.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] ICANN's bylaws say the committee provides advice to ICANN but the committee claims no authority over the servers or server operators.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The root zone file is a small (about 2 MB) data set at the apex of the Domain Name System, and its publication is the primary purpose of root name servers.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] It is not to be confused with the *root.hints* file used to bootstrap a resolver.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The contents of the root zone file is a list of names and numeric IP addresses of the root domain authoritative DNS servers for all top-level domains (TLDs) such as com, org, edu, and the country code top-level domains (it also includes that info for root domain, the dot).
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] On 12 December 2004, 773 different authoritative servers for the TLDs were listed.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Later the number of TLDs increased greatly.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] As of July 2020, the root zone consisted of 1511 useful TLDs (excluded are: 55 domains that are not assigned, 8 that are retired, and 11 test domains).
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] Other name servers forward queries for which they do not have any information about authoritative servers to a root name server.
[src:dnssec/root-name-server] The root name server, using its root zone file, answers with a referral to the authoritative servers for the appropriate TLD or with an indication that no such TLD exists.
